          <h2>How this clothing size converter works</h2>
          <p>Clothing sizes are not true “units” like centimeters or inches. They are labels that group ranges of body or garment measurements. This converter uses:</p>
          <ul>
            <li>Standard international size charts (US, UK, EU, Italy, France, Japan, INT S/M/L).</li>
            <li>Typical body measurements (bust, chest, waist, hips, foot length) for each labeled size.</li>
            <li>A matching algorithm that finds the closest equivalent size in other regions.</li>
          </ul>
          <p>Because brands differ, all conversions are approximate. Always check the brand’s own chart when available.</p>

          <h3>Step‑by‑step: converting your size</h3>
          <ol>
            <li>Select the <strong>category</strong> (e.g., Women – Tops, Men – Shoes).</li>
            <li>Choose the <strong>region</strong> where you know your size (US, UK, EU, etc.).</li>
            <li>Enter your <strong>current size label</strong> (e.g., 8, 38, M, 9.5) or click one of the quick sizes.</li>
            <li>Click <strong>Convert size</strong>.</li>
            <li>Read the equivalent sizes in other regions and compare the suggested body measurements.</li>
          </ol>

          <h2>Practical tips for better fit</h2>
          <h3>1. Prioritize measurements over labels</h3>
          <p>Two garments with the same labeled size can have very different actual measurements. When possible, measure:</p>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Bust/chest:</strong> around the fullest part, tape parallel to the floor.</li>
            <li><strong>Waist:</strong> at the narrowest point.</li>
            <li><strong>Hips:</strong> around the fullest part of your hips and seat.</li>
            <li><strong>Inseam:</strong> from crotch to ankle along the inside leg.</li>
            <li><strong>Foot length:</strong> heel to longest toe while standing.</li>
          </ul>

          <h3>2. Consider fit and ease</h3>
          <p>Garments are designed with “ease” – extra room beyond body measurements. A slim‑fit shirt and a relaxed‑fit shirt with the same label may feel very different. If you are between sizes or prefer a looser fit, choose the larger converted size.</p>

          <h3>3. Regional quirks</h3>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>EU vs. Italy/France:</strong> Italian and French sizes are often 2 numbers lower than EU (e.g., EU 40 ≈ IT 44 ≈ FR 42 for men’s suits).</li>
            <li><strong>UK vs. US women’s:</strong> UK women’s sizes are usually 2 numbers smaller than US (US 8 ≈ UK 12).</li>
            <li><strong>Shoes:</strong> EU sizes are unisex; US/UK differ for men and women.</li>
          </ul>

          <h2>FAQ</h2>
          <h3>Are kids’ size conversions exact?</h3>
          <p>No. Kids grow quickly and brands use different age/height mappings. Treat kids’ conversions as rough guidance and always check height and chest/waist measurements.</p>

          <h3>What if my size is not listed?</h3>
          <p>Enter the closest size you see in your region. The converter will still show approximate equivalents. For half sizes or in‑between sizes, you may see two nearby options in other regions.</p>
